<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA22448F7A0F5760D9D0354" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="297" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA22448F7A0F5760D9D0354" blockId="11.[2050,2645,2542,2965]" lastBlockId="12.[90,1302,290,3008]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="297" pageId="11" pageNumber="296">
This species was first collected by the famous naturalist H. Butler in July 1965 at Parry Creek on 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF75EF52706CA0B93" box="[2301,2434,2774,2807]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">Ningbing</taxonomicName>
Station, Kimberley region, Western Australia. In 1988, D. J. Kitchener and N. Caputi described 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF7A0F4BD07D40A09" authorityName="Kitchener &amp; Caputi" authorityYear="1988" box="[2051,2204,2892,2925]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="woolleyae">P. woolleyae</taxonomicName>
, also recognizing 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF605F4BD077B0AF1" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
“ 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF7EAF485078D0AF1" box="[2121,2245,2932,2965]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
” as a species, and Kitchener duly formally raised 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF961F46A087E0AD8" box="[1730,1846,2971,3004]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
to a full species in the same year, based on morphology. There are currently six recognized species of dasyurid marsupial “false antechinuses:” 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FFA7FF41B09790D6F" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[1500,1585,3050,3083]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">bilarni</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF9E6F41B08590D6F" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1605,1809,3050,3083]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF886F41B08DB0D6F" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[1829,1939,3050,3083]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">mimulus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF804F41B07510D6F" box="[1959,2073,3050,3083]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF78FF41B072E0D6F" authorityName="Cooper, Aplin &amp; Adams" authorityYear="2000" box="[2092,2150,3050,3083]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roryi">roryi</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF71AF41B06640D6F" authorityName="Kitchener &amp; Caputi" authorityYear="1988" box="[2233,2348,3050,3083]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="woolleyae">woolleyae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF6E3F41B05450D6F" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[2368,2573,3050,3083]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FFA02F3E009470D56" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[1441,1551,3089,3122]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">mimulus</taxonomicName>
were initially placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF84DF3E007370D56" box="[2030,2175,3089,3122]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
, along with 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF689F3E005050D56" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[2346,2637,3089,3122]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">Parantechinus apicalis</taxonomicName>
. Nevertheless, G. H. H. Tate in 1947 erected a new genus (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF76AF3C906E90D3D" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[2249,2465,3128,3161]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
) for 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF648F3C909410DE5" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF9F0F39109890DE5" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" box="[1619,1729,3168,3201]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">mimulus</taxonomicName>
and a monotypic genus, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF784F39107A80DE5" box="[2087,2272,3168,3201]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
, for 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF686F39106CD0DE5" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[2341,2437,3168,3201]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
. W. D. L. Ride in 1964 placed all three species back under 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF7AFF37607D50DCC" box="[2060,2205,3207,3240]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
. Later, P. A. Woolley examined penile morphology of Ride’s 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF8E6F35F089D0DAB" box="[1861,2005,3246,3279]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
supergroup and maintained that 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF665F35F0AAC0D93" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FFA5AF32709060D93" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[1529,1614,3286,3319]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">bilarni</taxonomicName>
, the then undescribed “ 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF817F327076F0D93" box="[1972,2087,3286,3319]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
,” and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF72EF32707A50D93" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[2189,2285,3286,3319]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
formed a distinct group from other 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF9E1F30C099B0C7A" box="[1602,1747,3325,3358]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Antechinus</taxonomicName>
. M. Archer dutifully resurrected both of Tate’s genera, consigning 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FFA7FF2D409EF0C22" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[1500,1703,3365,3398]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
and “ 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF8A7F2D4083C0C22" box="[1796,1908,3365,3398]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
” to 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF819F2D407D90C22" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1978,2193,3365,3398]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF741F2D4067F0C22" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[2274,2359,3365,3398]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">bilarni</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF62AF2D406A10C22" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[2441,2537,3365,3398]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">apicalis</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF5BCF2D409630C09" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
. P. R. Baverstock and colleagues in 1982 used allozyme (isozyme) genetic data to confirm Tate’s proposed genera 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF86FF28907EB0CF1" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[1996,2211,3448,3477]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA2244FF744F28906E90CF1" box="[2279,2465,3448,3477]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="296" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
. Subsequent allozyme work suggested that the 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FD98FED30DE70027" box="[571,687,290,323]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">ningbing</taxonomicName>
was a distinct species. Kitchener’s morphological work corroborated the genetics several years later, and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FC64FEB80B15000E" box="[967,1117,329,362]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">P. ningbing</taxonomicName>
was formally raised to a full species. Direct sequencing of mtDNA and nDNA has been conducted over the last decade and suggests that 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FDD3FE690DAE00DD" authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="1954" box="[624,742,408,441]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Antechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilarni">P. bilarni</taxonomicName>
is very different genetically from 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FB1AFE690F8D0084" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Parantechinus</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FF7BFE4E0E140084" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[216,348,447,480]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Parantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apicalis">P. apicalis</taxonomicName>
) and all other species of 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FD1CFE4E0CDD0084" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[703,917,447,480]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FC06FE4E0B710084" authorityName="Kitchener &amp; Caputi" authorityYear="1988" box="[933,1081,447,480]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="woolleyae">P. woolleyae</taxonomicName>
was resolved as sister to all congeners; 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FE02FE170D7F0363" box="[417,567,486,519]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">P. ningbing</taxonomicName>
was resolved assister to a clade containing 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FB3DFE170FCA0354" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1906" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mimulus">P. mimulus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FF31FDE20EC90354" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[146,385,531,560]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">P. macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FE6DFDE20D610354" authorityName="Cooper, Aplin &amp; Adams" authorityYear="2000" box="[462,553,531,560]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roryi">P. roryi</taxonomicName>
. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA52448FFF8FDC40E0903C2" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" type="distribution">
<caption id="36A6665FFFA52448FFF8FDC40E0903C2" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6608156" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6608156" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6608156/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" targetBox="[1436,2027,2547,2961]" targetPageId="11">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA52448FFF8FDC40E0903C2" blockId="12.[90,1302,290,3008]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA52448FFF8FDC40E430332" bold="true" box="[91,267,565,598]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">Distribution.</emphasis>
Australia, in the Kimberley region of Western Australia and NW Northern Territory, also on Augustus and Heywood Is in the Bonaparte Archipelago off the Kimberley coast.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA52448FFF8FD410C73051B" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" type="description">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA52448FFF8FD410C73051B" blockId="12.[90,1302,290,3008]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA52448FFF8FD410E1103A9" bold="true" box="[91,345,688,717]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 9-10 cm (males) and 8-9 cm (females), tail 8-9 cm (males) and 7.5-9 cm (females); weight 20-25 g (males) and 15-20 g (females). There is slightly sexual dimorphism for size. Fur of the Ningbing Pseudantechinus is pale grayish-brown above and below; there are chestnut patches behind ears. The Ningbing Pseudantechinus is similar to the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FC73FCA30B80020F" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1896" box="[976,1224,850,875]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Phascogale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macdonnellensis">P. macdonnellensis</taxonomicName>
), but its tail is longer (relative to head-body length), with long hairs covering its base. Remainder oftail in the Ningbing Pseudantechinusis sparsely haired and has a slightly scaly appearance. Male Ningbing Pseudantechinuses have accessory erectile tissue that does not form an appendage to the penis, and females have four nipples in their pouches. These characteristics differ from those of Rory’s Pseudantechinus (FP. roryz) and the Fat-tailed Pseudantechinus, in which females have six nipples and male accessory erectile tissue forms an appendage to the penis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA52448FFFEFB750B000754" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="626636D7FFA52448FFFEFB750B000754" blockId="12.[90,1302,290,3008]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">
<emphasis id="50ADEAC5FFA52448FFFEFB750F8405C1" bold="true" box="[93,204,1156,1189]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297">Habitat.</emphasis>
Rocky habitat in limestone and sandstone outcrops in a variety of vegetation types. At Mitchell Plateau and Prince Regent Nature Reserve, Western Australia, the 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FFFDFB220FAB0590" box="[94,227,1235,1268]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ningbing">Ningbing</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FF4EFB220E930590" authorityName="Tate" authorityYear="1947" box="[237,475,1235,1268]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasyuridae" genus="Pseudantechinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dasyuromorphia" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudantechinus</taxonomicName>
was collected in low open eucalypt woodland with 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FB10FB220A5B0590" box="[1203,1299,1235,1268]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Meliaceae" genus="Owenia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Owenia</taxonomicName>
vernicosa (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FF4AFB0E0E360478" box="[233,382,1279,1308]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Meliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Meliaceae</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FE3BFB0E0D510478" box="[408,537,1279,1308]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Moraceae" genus="Ficus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">Ficus spp.</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FD90FB0E0D8C0478" box="[563,708,1279,1308]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Moraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Moraceae</taxonomicName>
), and 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FCBDFB0E0CFB0478" box="[798,947,1279,1308]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Acacia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">Acacia spp.</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FC6DFB0E0B1F0478" box="[974,1111,1279,1308]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
). These trees grew over a sparse shrub layer above a moderately dense ground cover of spinifex (
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FFC9FAB80F83040E" box="[106,203,1353,1386]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Triodia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Triodia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A5D94D54FFA52448FF7DFAB80E19040E" authorityName="Barnhart" authorityYear="1895" baseAuthorityName="R.Br." box="[222,337,1353,1386]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
) hummock grass with “sorghum” grass variously present. At other localities in western Kimberley, most specimens have been captured in riparian situations, typically in low, open woodland over low, open shrubland and moderately dense spinifex hummock grassland on sandstone and limestone. At Ningbing, specimens were collected along limestone ridges and on a sandstone outcrop with low open shrubs over a ground cover of mixed grass, shrubs, and emergent trees.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2AC3655CFFA52448FFFDF9C70B6B0733" box="[94,1059,1590,1623]" pageId="12" pageNumber="297" type="food_feeding">
